# FILE: `runtime/stateStore.js`

Create this file and paste this EXACTLY:

```js
const state = {
  currentNodeId: null,

  inventory: [],

  flags: {},

  rewards: []
};

export function getState() {
  return state;
}

export function setCurrentNode(nodeId) {
  state.currentNodeId = nodeId;
}

export function addItem(item) {
  state.inventory.push(item);
}

export function setFlag(key, value = true) {
  state.flags[key] = value;
}

export function addReward(reward) {
  state.rewards.push(reward);
}
```

---

# WHAT THIS FILE DOES

This becomes the first centralized runtime state layer.

Right now it owns:

```txt
- current node
- inventory
- flags
- rewards
```

Later it will expand to:

* timers
* checkpoints
* save/load persistence
* analytics hooks
* multiplayer sync
* runtime snapshots

But not yet.

---

# WHY THIS MATTERS

This prevents:

* random global variables
* renderer-owned state
* node-owned state
* DOM-owned gameplay logic

That separation is one of the most important V3 architectural upgrades.

---

# IMPORTANT RULE

From this point forward:

## Gameplay state should ONLY change through store functions.

GOOD:

```js
setCurrentNode("portal_001");
```

BAD:

```js
state.currentNodeId = "portal_001";
```

Even though both technically work.

The wrapper functions are what preserve runtime discipline later.

---

# IMPORTANT PHILOSOPHY

Right now:
we are optimizing for:

```txt
clarity
predictability
separation
```

NOT:

* over-engineering
* abstraction perfection
* framework complexity

Small clean systems first.

